            "tips_for_improvement": [
                {
                    "video_time": 3.999522,
                    "list": "['And the guy on the right is using the stick brush.', 'So the stick brush lets you brush really high up the holes, kind of saves you the energy of having to climb up there and brush them by hand.']",
                    "expert_uid": "kz25yw",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 8.708509,
                    "list": "['Brushing the holds strategically based on how they plan to use them.', 'Trying to get as close as possible to the next hold before moving.']",
                    "expert_uid": "50lpbg",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 11.750037,
                    "list": "[\"It's always nice to kind of brush your holds before an attempt.\", 'That way you can take off any excess chalk that might be on the holds.', 'That way you have a better grip on the holds altogether between your hands and the handhold.']",
                    "expert_uid": "2z4v0b",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 29.954223,
                    "list": "[\"He's grabbing the top of this hold where you can see this bottom part kind of rounds up the cup or bowl.\", 'It looks kind of like an awkward stance.', 'His fingers are super extended.', \"His thumb's doing this weird thing on the underside.\", 'It looks just like a more challenging way to do this first move.', 'His thighs maybe get higher and that being maybe eight inches, six inches higher on the hold is gonna be better.', 'Definitely seems like an awkward grip.', \"You can see how it's like bending his elbow, which just kind of seems like he's maybe taking it also then bending his, or bending his wrist.\", 'Kind of just a weird play right there.']",
                    "expert_uid": "kz25yw",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 30.194372,
                    "list": "['Having a thumb catch on the hold provides an opportunity to gain more control through the rest of your body.', 'The thumb acts as an opposition to the top four fingers and ease the climber in manipulating their hips and gaining a higher body position.']",
                    "expert_uid": "2vefmg",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 31.730063,
                    "list": "[\"he can't really fully relax on this hold\", \"he's not very opposite of pose\", \"it'd be interesting to see how hard he's pushing down with his right foot as well\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "kz25yw",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 33.025008,
                    "list": "[\"he's not completely transferring his body weight over onto that higher left foot\", 'transfer his body weight onto his left foot much more before bringing up his right hand']",
                    "expert_uid": "2z4v0b",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 33.280261,
                    "list": "[\"They're rushing this move a tiny bit.\", \"They're not really flagging out far enough with the right foot down here inside of screen.\", 'That would allow them to move the right hand to this hold a little slower.', \"They catch it with quite a bit of force, which it's early in the climb.\", 'Doing these kind of moves early in a climb can make it really difficult to finish the climb because too much energy has been expended at the start.']",
                    "expert_uid": "50lpbg",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 33.504536,
                    "list": "['He is climbing very heavily focused on his upper body instead of relaxing, kind of driving down through his feet and getting opposite of pose.', 'Chances are if he had placed a right foot well, as he moved his right hand up, he would have had this little mini kind of rip off the wall where he would have had to like compensate more with his arms and core to keep himself into the wall.']",
                    "expert_uid": "kz25yw",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 35.816561,
                    "list": "['The clammer is compensating by using a lot of upper body strength to reach the next hold. I would not recommend this approach as it uses up a lot of energy and fights against the natural swing of the body.']",
                    "expert_uid": "2z4v0b",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 36.967295,
                    "list": "[\"You need to lock in your feet in order to achieve a move like this where you're all crossed up\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "2vefmg",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 39.534134,
                    "list": "['concern about the placement of his right foot', 'not wanting to see him barn door off the wall']",
                    "expert_uid": "kz25yw",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
