                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 50.737531,
                    "list": "['slowly work to get his weight shifted', 'having a wide stance', 'shift his weight over to the right', 'create a new tension spot', 'anchor on this right hand', 'get his left foot up']",
                    "expert_uid": "kz25yw",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 51.288775,
                    "list": "['Trying again, get a little more leverage over the hold.', \"So the hand can wear out really quickly. If this is how they're holding onto things a lot.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "50lpbg",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 53.573419,
                    "list": "[\"sometimes when you're climbing, you cannot avoid being in a very strenuous position with both arms in a bent position\", 'try to make sure that a lot of body weight stays on your feet, especially if your feet are in the middle of your arms']",
                    "expert_uid": "2z4v0b",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 54.184285,
                    "list": "[\"The climber didn't spend that much time looking at the feet as they swapped from right to left.\", 'So the left foot was not placed optimally on that hold.', \"When that foot pops off, this is a harder position for them to maintain unless they're a very, very strong individual.\", \"This is also a weird injury risk position because they're in a pretty heavy finger load spot where having that sudden shock load, that eccentric motion pulling the fingers open really quickly, that's where you can see finger injuries occurring in climbers.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "50lpbg",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 54.245238,
                    "list": "['But they were just pulling a little too hard with this left foot here.', \"There's always a perfect position for each move.\", 'It looks like this climber was maybe just putting too much weight into their left foot or pulling too hard out from the wall with the left foot.', 'It was an unforeseen error of the climber.', 'The left foot cut and that was too much for the climber to overcome on this attempt.']",
                    "expert_uid": "2vefmg",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 54.267795,
                    "list": "[\"And it looks like he tried to swap the feet and maybe the left foot didn't stick as well as he'd hope or maybe he wasn't that careful with it or just kind of assumed it was in a good spot.\", 'We can see as he brings his left hand over to grab this next hold his feet cut again causing him to rip out from the wall.', \"That's why it's so important to really be staring down our feet and knowing exactly where they're placed.\", \"But it's the same for the feet. We want to be able to effectively stand and push and pull through our toes.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "kz25yw",
                    "video_name": "uniandes_bouldering_012_3"
                }
            ]
        },
