                },
                {
                    "video_time": 55.720216,
                    "list": "['moving their hand a little bit closer to the bridge for better volume and resonance on high strings', 'plucking higher strings slightly more and lower strings slightly less']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 73.243498,
                    "list": "['Take more time before starting and moving on to the next section']",
                    "expert_uid": "tja8o9",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 81.794304,
                    "list": "['The right hand here starts to become a little bit uncoordinated.', 'The middle of each section starts to feel a bit compressed.', \"So they're definitely rushing a tiny bit.\", \"But there's so many notes that I think it's a little bit more noticeable.\", \"Advice would just be to keep practicing slowly so that in these moments when you're going fast, you really have an understanding of what your right hand is doing.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "tja8o9",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 95.219739,
                    "list": "['I think the tempo starts to get here a little bit too fast for this player.', \"I think if they slow down enough that they should have the technical ability, but right now it seems like it's faster than the opening section.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "tja8o9",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 95.448736,
                    "list": "['You can see here how far up the middle and ring finger is coming from the string.', \"And that's what is resulting in this scratchy nail sound on those higher strings.\", 'Ideally we would want to not pluck those fingers too far up so that we can still grab the string and get a good contact point with the nail and not get that scratchy nail sound.']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 110.99106,
                    "list": "['The performer is plucking the string too far up, out away from the guitar.', 'When you pluck up, the recoil of the string will then slap back against those frets and result in that buzzing sound.', 'Ideally, we would want the pluck to be down across the neck.']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 126.033671,
                    "list": "['the guitarist is plucking the A string and the D string before their finger has fully pressed down the note', 'the left hand pressing down the string to the fingerboard just a millisecond or so before the string is']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 146.881347,
                    "list": "['when the left hand was lagging behind the right hand', 'So you cannot pluck the string until the left hand has fully arrived to the fret.']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 174.053247,
                    "list": "[\"we're not hearing every note in the right hand clearly\", 'make sure that the left hand is firmly pressing the string to the fret', 'play the lower string softer and the higher strings louder to achieve an even tone']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 180.157339,
                    "list": "[\"the guitarist needs to go back through this and adjust their finger stroke to meet the needs of Each note and each string that he is playing so that it's a smooth arpeggio\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 180.407816,
                    "list": "['It starts to rush a little bit', 'The top line starts to unravel', 'Not become as clear', 'Practice slowly', 'Isolate a certain line']",
                    "expert_uid": "tja8o9",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 199.513115,
                    "list": "[\"we don't want to increase the tempo\", 'keep a steady tempo throughout the piece', 'keep the rhythm consistent', 'keep arpeggios and sound consistent']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 215.115543,
                    "list": "[\"the player could use their forearm rotation, like turning a doorknob, to help them get their fingers to become down faster onto the string as they're moving back.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "tja8o9",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_5"
                },
