            "tips_for_improvement": [
                {
                    "video_time": 2.061973,
                    "list": "['body shape and the stance is quite high and it is not very athletic', 'a lot of weight has been put on a flat foot', 'we have a straight knee, we have a straight leg', 'we have shoulders up high and we have, not super important, but the head is super high', 'what I would like to see in this stance is maybe a player being on his toes so the heel is off the floor', 'This will then cause the knees to bend slightly, it will have elasticity in the muscles and the player will be better placed to react to maybe a misplaced pass or a misplaced touch']",
                    "expert_uid": "7a277n",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 2.149391,
                    "list": "[\"The player's high stance and straight line in the body affect their center of gravity and hinder their ability to move quickly from left to right or right to left.\", \"The player's straight knee and flat foot on the ground limit their ability to adjust quickly to a misplaced touch or pass.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "7a277n",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 3.395991,
                    "list": "['What we would like to see or prefer to see is as the player is about to play the pass to make sure that his non-kicking foot is moving first closer to the ball.', \"When we reach for the ball, that affects the contact point between the foot and the ball and will ultimately lead to less consistency with the quality of the pass, with accuracy and weight because we can't get our foot in a position that allows us to then strike through in the direction of the ball.\", 'It then also affects our ability to then move and accelerate away after the pass quickly.']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 4.13197,
                    "list": "[\"Player doesn't move a ball with enough speed.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "gnjtek",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 4.780191,
                    "list": "['return it to him in a way that he can pass the ball efficiently back here in one touch to keep the tempo and the speed of the exercise going and preventing it from slowing down']",
                    "expert_uid": "3u75lz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 5.726967,
                    "list": "['The non-kicking foot should move away from the direction of the ball.', 'Open up the hips to face the direction you want to go.', 'Bend the knees to lower the center of gravity for more protection against pressure and better ability to move quickly with the ball.']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 6.330745,
                    "list": "[\"knee is relatively close, okay, we'd like that knee to be maybe a slightly further forward so it's on top of the ball\", 'move the non-kicking foot in line with the first touch to get closer to the ball']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 6.704577,
                    "list": "['The person receiving the ball needs to start turning their hips and torso as they take the first touch with the ball.']",
                    "expert_uid": "gnjtek",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 8.477292,
                    "list": "['Move the non-kicking foot back and start to turn towards the direction he wants to play his pass.']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 8.51521,
                    "list": "[\"The one recommendation that I would make is the angle he's receiving on\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "3u75lz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 8.635383,
                    "list": "['The first touch establishes your plan and sets the stage for your interaction with the ball.', 'The last touch signifies the result of your interaction with the ball and the final execution of your decision.']",
                    "expert_uid": "t5y5xs",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 9.30125,
                    "list": "[\"ideally, as this ball is taken with his first touch into this position, we'd want to move our body in a similar line to the ball just to get our feet in a better position to give ourselves options and a better base for our technique of playing the pass with the outside.\", \"his right foot moved in a direction away from the line of the ball, which then leads to the situation where the player's distance from the non-kicking foot to the ball is further.\", \"This then leads to a straighter leg as we end up reaching for the ball and with the extended leg that leads to our ability as a player to generate less power and control because we don't get our knee in line with the ball, we can't really get our toe pointed down and then make clean contact and strike through the direction of the pass.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 9.435501,
                    "list": "[\"person receiving doesn't turn their hips as they receive the ball and means they end up being square for the next pass instead of sideways\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "gnjtek",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 11.415159,
                    "list": "['Both legs should have slight knee bend to allow for better mobility and direction with the first touch.', 'The non-kicking foot should be raised slightly off the ground to improve balance and protection of the ball.']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 12.117821,
                    "list": "['Because the leg is straight and the non-kicking foot is still too far away from the ball, that means that our knee is not in a position closer to the ball or over the ball.', 'As we reach now through the ball, it restricts our ability to follow through in the direction of the ball.', 'This foot making the pass is going to have to then settle down onto the ground first, regain our balance before we can then move into the space.']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 13.07408,
                    "list": "['Refine first and last touch using efficient touch pattern', 'Apply one and two touch pattern approach', 'Repetition to enhance specific set of touches and touch surfaces']",
                    "expert_uid": "t5y5xs",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 13.197597,
                    "list": "['The weight of the pass is very slow, a little pace.', 'To improve the weight of the pass, the player needs to punch through the line of the intended direction of the pass, with his foot locked in the same position from the contact through to the follow through.', 'The player should use the dorsal surface or the outer top part of the foot to strike through the middle of the ball.', \"It's important that we get the non-kicking foot closer to the ball to allow the knee to get over the ball with the kicking foot.\", \"If the feet are too far apart, then that's going to lead it to be very difficult for the player to step through the line of the ball and get the knee position correctly and close to it.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 14.164248,
                    "list": "[\"non-kicking foot is moved back from the line of the ball and it's starting to also turn towards the direction of the intended pass\", 'create the space for the ball to travel through with his first touch', 'hips and the body start to turn towards the intended direction of the first touch', 'better balance, better protection of the ball and the ability to then accelerate with more speed in the direction of the first touch']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 14.170718,
                    "list": "['Receiving the ball on a different angle with his weaker foot', 'Judging the weight of the ball across his body', 'Improving coordination for a difficult return pass']",
                    "expert_uid": "3u75lz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 14.306188,
                    "list": "['The player is off the central line here']",
