                },
                {
                    "video_time": 19.989548,
                    "list": "['The non-kicking foot is slightly withdrawn and starting to turn with his toe pointing out, which allows for the hips to start to rotate', \"We'd probably want to see the foot move a little further back with the toe starting to turn a little bit further to the right\", 'I would like for there to be just a little bit more knee bend both in the receiving foot and the non-kicking foot', 'The knee bend also allows our hips to get a little bit lower to the ground, lower centre of gravity, provide better balance and protection']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 21.056177,
                    "list": "['The player should work on their footwork and movements after the first touch to limit the time between receiving the ball and releasing the pass.', 'The player should focus on having a more natural running pattern as they move with the ball.']",
                    "expert_uid": "umjlsz",
                    "video_name": "cmu_soccer06_2"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 21.189508,
                    "list": "['The contact point with the ball was a little closer, higher up the outside part, closer to the ankle, as opposed to the dorsal surface', 'Hitting the ball with the full outside surface of the foot and definitely closer to the ankle leads to less consistency and accuracy', \"The foot is planting now to the ground, kind of square to the ball. So although it's pointing in the direction of where we want to go next, we haven't been able to really strike through the line of the pass\", \"The quality of the pass will be affected because we haven't been able to point our toe down and strike through the line of the ball before we then move into this space\"]",
