                },
                {
                    "video_time": 74.362294,
                    "list": "['the guitarist is making really great contact with his thumb in the right hand', 'which is why we hear that nice, really resonant low strings when he plucks them']",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_10"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 90.146193,
                    "list": "['This is a really great example of the motion with which the fingers in the right hand should pluck the string.', 'every time the guitarist plucks a string, his finger is coming backwards into the hand, not being plucked up.', 'this slight curve of the wrist and where he has a guitar positioned on his arm allows his hand to hang over the strings', 'then he can pluck just inwards toward his hand instead of having to pluck up.', \"So it's pretty much perfect right hand technique.\"]",
                    "expert_uid": "vsudlg",
                    "video_name": "upenn_0707_Guitar_2_10"
                },
                {
                    "video_time": 90.734957,
                    "list": "['The guitarist uses their right hand to alternate between the thumb, first finger, and second finger', \"They're also doing this very rhythmically.\"]",
